##PageID 1532
TEXT_content
 <p>Weitere Informationen zum Film und zu den Bestellmöglichkeiten finden Sie auf der Webseite des SWR zum Thema „Hunger“.<br />
        In der Mediathek der ARD können Sie sich den Film in voller Länge anschauen.</p>

##PageID 1580
##PageID 3381
TEXT_content
 <p>Sound disposal reduces health risks and protects environment</p>
        <p>Although insecticides are designed to boost crop yields, they jeopardise the lives of millions of people if they are inadequately stored, pass their use-by date or are disposed of incorrectly. The same is true of hazardous waste in contaminated industrial sites that are no longer in use. GIZ's work in the area of toxic waste disposal helps reduce health risks and protect the environment.</p>
        <p>'The barrels were not properly sealed and the content made its way into the ground, from where it was washed into the nearby river,' recalls GIZ expert Wolfgang Schimpf. The Mozambican authorities discovered the waste in Beira, which had been forgotten during the chaos brought about by the civil war, by sheer coincidence. The labels on the barrels were illegible. The unidentifiable content posed a serious threat to local inhabitants, as it was only a matter of time before the toxic waste made its way into the food chain.</p>
        <p>Agricultural pesticides generate toxic waste that are frequently stockpiled, and in many cases are obsolete or are not stored correctly. They jeopardise human health and pose a constant threat to the environment.  GIZ has decades of experience in safely disposing of hazardous waste. It has helped many partner countries to dispose of toxic waste in an environmentally sound manner. Governments and institutions frequently approach GIZ directly to request assistance.</p>
        <p>In Mozambique, for example, GIZ worked on behalf of the German Government to analyse stockpiled pesticides, which it turned out, contained highly toxic Azodrin/DDT. As no suitable facilities were available in Eastern Africa, the toxic waste was shipped to Wales and England, together with the barrels, the polluted wooden pallets and contaminated soil, where they were disposed of in special high-temperature incineration plants.</p>
        <p>In Mexico, GIZ advised the government and local authorities on redeveloping contaminated sites in inner cities. The sites – formerly home to thriving industries – had to be decontaminated to make them suitable for housing construction. Swift action was paramount: if the responsible authorities had dragged their heels, socially disadvantaged population groups from rural areas would have established illegal settlements, thereby putting their health at serious risk.</p>
        <p>In the city of Aguascalientes, the work carried out by the national rail operator in its workshops had contaminated both the soil and the groundwater over many decades. When work to redevelop the 88-hectare site first started, the partner side only had very limited capacities to safely dispose of toxic, hazardous waste.  GIZ advisors helped the Mexican authorities to safely store several thousand tonnes of heavy metals and other toxic substances in hazardous waste landfills. In 2007, the previously contaminated site was redeveloped into the 'Tres Centurias' park, which is home to several sports grounds, an open-air theatre, a hospital and expansive green areas.</p>
        <p>Untreated hazardous waste is highly toxic, and poses an acute risk to both human beings and the environment. GIZ's redevelopment work is based on international standards such as the Basel Convention controlling transboundary movements of hazardous wastes and their disposal. In many cases, renewing contaminated sites is just one step on the path to achieving overarching objectives such as preventing hazardous waste production, developing monitoring criteria and technologies, improving management, and running seminars and training courses. These objectives play a key role in building awareness among politicians, authorities, managers and the general public of the problems of toxic waste.</p>

##PageID 3415
TEXT_content
 <p>GIZ is keen to make Eschborn Dialogue a green event, which is why most of the food and beverages served are regionally sourced and organically produced. We also ensure the efficient use of energy and water in the conference rooms. We offset the carbon emissions generated by participants’ travel to and from the event.</p>

